    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="952"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d952">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.946 Rag Rugs/78</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sayre</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Japanese Ambassador</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Saito</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-26">June 26,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: The statement made on June 7
                    by a member of your staff to an officer of the Department<note n="58"
                        xml:id="d952fn58">Not printed.</note> that the <pb facs="1087" n="975"
                        xml:id="pg_975"/> Japanese manufacturers and exporters of cotton rugs would
                    be prepared to extend for another year the arrangement to limit exports of
                    cotton rugs from Japan to the United States has been noted with
                    appreciation.</p>
                <p>In acknowledging the cooperative spirit displayed by these manufacturers and
                    exporters, I would like to have you know that a survey is now being made of the
                    American cotton rug industry in an effort to determine if possible whether there
                    has been an improvement during the past year in the condition of that industry.
                    We hope that the survey will conclusively indicate that there has been a
                    substantial increase in total consumption in the United States during the year,
                    and if such should be the case, we would expect some measure of increased
                    participation by Japanese exporters in the American market.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis B. Sayre</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
